{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5d887e4b-b670-4e4e-85c7-65c71e06712a","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's going on:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID generation strategy**. Azure DevOps tracks history by test ID, so every test looks \"new.\" To restore history, add this to your project:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\nOr accept the new IDs and let history rebuild over time.\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — no test is running yet, so `TestName` throws `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it misleadingly returned the name of whichever test happened to trigger init first.\n\nYour `SetupTests.cs` line 13 hits this exactly. Fix: guard or remove the access:\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // ← throws in v4\n```\n\n### 3. Other v4 breaking changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **Parallelism** | Assembly-level parallelism is **on by default**. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.MethodLevel)]` or `DoNotParallelize` if tests aren't thread-safe. |\n| **`[ClassCleanup]` timing** | Now runs at **end of class** by default (was end of assembly). Use `[ClassCleanup(ClassCleanupBehavior.EndOfAssembly)]` to restore old behavior. |\n| **Package consolidation** | Single `MSTest` package replaces `MSTest.TestFramework` + `MSTest.TestAdapter`. You've already done this correctly. |\n| **`DataRow` validation** | Stricter type checking on `[DataRow]` arguments — mismatched types that silently coerced in v3 now fail. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Read-only in `[AssemblyInitialize]`/`[ClassInitialize]` contexts. |\n\n---\n\nWant me to fix `SetupTests.cs` to be v4-compatible (e.g., remove the `TestName` access in `ClassInit`)?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4e75658e-cb6c-4750-85a3-90f0bd970233","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has two specific issues and wants general guidance on MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me address each:\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps (lost history)**: In MSTest v4, the default **test ID generation strategy** changed. MSTest v3 used a legacy ID scheme, while v4 switched to a new deterministic ID scheme. Since Azure DevOps tracks test history by test ID, changing the ID scheme makes all tests appear as new. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` back to the legacy value, or accept the new IDs.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]**: In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context**, not associated with any specific test method. Accessing `TestName` on it throws an `InvalidOperationException` because there's no test running yet at class initialization time. \n\nIn v3, it would return the name of the first test that triggered the class init, which was misleading anyway. Beyond these two issues, there are several other changes worth noting: the unified `MSTest` NuGet package now replaces the separate framework and adapter packages, `DataRow` validation is stricter, `DeploymentItem` behavior has shifted, `TestContext.Properties` is read-only in certain contexts, assembly-level parallelism runs by default, and `[ClassCleanup]` timing has changed.","outputTokens":990,"requestId":"7C21:1EA0BA:186B6B6:1BD088B:69F95FC9"},"id":"59a43f09-a9f3-407e-be46-8022ce1b7bd0","timestamp":"2026-05-05T03:11:27.056Z","parentId":"37a4e41d-8fca-441c-92f8-1f0d0284192a"}
